  "text": "These findings are in line with the literature, which emphasizes the importance of time savings to users. [CITATION_1] , summarizing from Kvavnik and Caruso's 2005 ECAR study, states that \"these findings support the notion that students place the highest value in those features that make their lives easier and their learning more convenient\" (p. 8). [CITATION_2] comment that instructors who independently and freely adopt a new teaching tool generally do so because they expect an \"efficiency benefit\" (p. 13). They also point out that instructors adopting a new tool need a genuine or expected \"efficiency payoff\" (p. 15) if they are to commit to learning and using the new tool.",
